                  Can you take us back to the beginning? How did you get started?
                  



The idea actually resulted from a problem I saw in my own family. My brother and his wife ride bikes together, but it was difficult for her to keep up on the hills and to travel as far and as fast as my brother. My brother built an electric-assisted bike for her, which solved the problem and their rides together became more frequent and enjoyable for them both. Talking about this one day, we realized that a lot of other people would benefit from the same technology. So we researched the issue and started the company with about $100,000 of our own money.

Prior to founding EVELO, my brother and I started, grew, and eventually sold two other companies during the last decade. From our initial investment we’ve grown EVELO organically, relying only on our own revenue and profits for the first 3-1/2 years. The result is sales of about $6 million, with $1 million in sales in just the last quarter alone.




                  Who is your competition?
                  



We have two different types of competitors:

 1. Traditional Bike Companies (e.g., Trek, Specialized, Schwinn)

The one thing that makes traditional bike companies so strong is the same thing that makes their electric bike offerings and distribution so weak -- their dealers are true cycling enthusiasts who frequently started their bike shop because of that passion. The vast majority of traditional bike shops today, however, tend to think of electric bikes as a form of "cheating".This trickles down the entire supply chain. A bike company may have only 1 or 2 electric bike models, resulting in limited choice. Bike shop owners and staff are not thrilled about selling electric-powered products. Customers typically start their e-bike research online, rather than by going to a local store.Given all of this, if you visit any traditional bike store and ask them about their electric bike distribution, they will either have no interest or they will say that they tried but couldn’t really find a way to sell a meaningful number of e-bikes.Even with traditional bike companies not finding a viable market for electric bikes, we still take steps to differentiate ourselves.

- Laser focus on electric bikes and direct-to-consumer distribution.- We only sell electric bikes, making us the natural choice for customers looking for one. Based on our findings, many people begin their research on electric bikes online rather than by going to a traditional store. This allows us to capture their attention and trust first.- In terms of distribution, traditional bike brands are inflexible, given that they have to rely on an existing network of dealers. As a result, any bike sold directly at a brick-and-mortar dealer carries a markup of up to 40% over a direct-to-consumer brand like ours. This allows us to offer a lower price to the customer while maintaining a higher profit margin.

2. Electric Bike Companies (e.g., Pedego, Stromer, Faraday)

With competing electric bike companies, we focus on the ways we can win over a customer.

1.  Technology - although there is no such thing as a perfect bike for everyone, certain technological features do make a bike more appealing to a wider population.

- Automatic Transmission -- Many of our customers are new to cycling, so we focus on making our products incredibly easy to use with no learning curve. For example, many customers tell us that they dislike the traditional gearing mechanisms used on bikes. Consequently, we have done away with traditional gearing by using the NuVinci Harmony CVT instead. This is basically an automatic transmission like we find in cars, but designed for a bike, changing the gears for the rider automatically (http://www.evelo.com/evelo-difference/nuvinci-harmony-automatic-transmission/).

- Mid-Drive Motor Design -- We also chose a different motor design than most other e-bike companies. They use traditional hub motors because they are cheaper and easier to source. Instead, we offer a mid-drive option. This offers a lot of advantages: better climbing of the hills, better range, ability to use a smaller battery and still get great range, and being able to take advantage of all of the gears on a bike (http://www.evelo.com/evelo-difference/advantages-mid-drive-motor-vs-hub-motor/). The use of a mid-drive motor, combined with the NuVinci Harmony, is a major draw for many of our customers.

- Omni Wheel -- In addition to a line of complete electric bikes, we recently launched the new Omni Wheel (http://omni.evelo.com). By replacing the front wheel with the Omni, anyone can convert a traditional bike into an electric one in just 20 minutes. No technical skills are required, and it comes at a fraction of the price of a complete bike. With the addition of the Omni Wheel, we can meet the needs of virtually any customer at any price point.

2. Distribution -- Technology is only 50% of the equation. Even if we had the best bike tech out there, if we can't sell it at the right price point to the right customer, we would still be out of luck.

- Direct-to-Consumer Distribution Model – selling directly to customers in an online marketplace lets us consistently price our products at 25%+ less than brands at brick-and-mortar stores, while also offering a better overall product (more power, more range). This allows us to scale faster and more efficiently such that with modest increases in team size, we grow significantly due to the structure of our work.

- Ambassador Program – We counteract one big advantage that dealers at bike stores have with this program. It connects existing EVELO owners with potential customers for test rides. Our Ambassadors (existing owners) make money every time they complete the test ride process, as well as every time a test ride turns into a sale. We are the only company in the industry where our customers can actually earn an income off their bike purchase -- to the tune of $400 to $600 per year on average.

- Subscription Model – We are currently exploring a subscription-based offering that would also enable our customers to get a perfect electric bike for themselves for as low as $99 per month (about the price of a monthly transit pass) without sacrificing the quality or specs of the product.




                  How do you acquire customers?
                  



We’ve worked hard to develop a core strength in digital marketing. Our team of 14 people is split fairly evenly between those from the traditional bike industry and those from the e-commerce space. Most of our marketing is oriented around search, search engine optimization, email marketing, content marketing, and social media. We provide as much information on and through our website as we possibly can to both prospects and existing customers. Our Ambassador program is the only major offline component of our customer acquisition approach. The end result of all this is a typical acquisition cost of 9% (or $300) on an average purchase of $2,800.




                  Could you tell us about your production process?
                  



We currently work with two factories – one in China and the other in Taiwan -- each focused on different product lines. We’ve built excellent relationships with them and team members periodically visit to provide in-person contact. The completed bikes are shipped to our warehouse/office in Seattle by container ship. Orders are customized and shipped directly from our Seattle warehouse and office via either UPS or FedEx to customers.

Our partners are a key piece in our continuing growth. In a capital-intensive business such as EVELO’s, with a goal of achieving economies of scale to slingshot even greater opportunities, we need additional capital. Over the past couple of years, we have fine-tuned our advertising efforts, our logistics, purchasing, etc. -- learning what works, what doesn't, and how to keep costs down. Fast growth at this point depends on focusing on customer acquisition to increase our volume with our suppliers, which will actually drive down production costs. It's win-win situation -- more customers mean we can produce our product for less and we can sell it for less, which in turn will attract more customers. Once we go from $3 million to about $10 million in sales, we’ll start seeing significant drops in our production costs.




                  For those that are completely unfamiliar with your space, can you talk about what the market looks like, and where you see it going in the next 5 years?
                  



One of the things we joke about internally is that an electric bike is the best-selling electric vehicle in the world that nobody in the U.S. knows about. Although the global electric bike market involves $50 billion a year, with 40 million electric bikes sold last year, and a growth rate of 20% year-over-year, the market in the U.S. lags behind the rest of the world. Some companies that started out 3-4 years before we did now reach sales of $40 to $50 million per year.

Some impressive growth in the U.S. market during the past year or so, however, makes this the perfect time for us to expand. In the U.S., interest in electric bikes is fuelled by three major trends. The first is the search for alternative means of transport in growing urban centers, where car ownership is expensive, parking space limited, and rush-hour traffic leads to gridlock. Second, electric transport in general is becoming mainstream for environmental and other reasons. Tesla’s entry into the electric vehicle field succeeded in bringing together technology that is acceptably priced, of proven quality, and visually attractive – paving the way for increased general interest in alternative transport as a whole. The third trend is a growing emphasis on staying health, fit, and active. With a large number of baby boomers now hitting retirement age, staying active and fit may involve age-related challenges that electric bikes help overcome.

Over the next five years, even as electric and hybrid cars become more the norm, some people will still choose an electric bike for most travel, especially as urban areas continue to develop more of a biking culture with increased use of dedicated bike lanes and trails. Zipping past rush-hour traffic will still be appealing whether the cars in traffic are gas powered or electric. And, of course, an electric bike still will help older riders keep fit and active, something that is beyond the capabilities of an electric car. Lifestyle choices offered by electric bikes, such as leisurely rides on trails and paths, a secondary transportation device for RV owners, and quick-and-easy errand-running, will greatly expand.

In essence, the presence of electric and hybrid cars in the market will be a catalyst for growing interest in other environment-friendly options, like electric bikes. We see nothing but growth here in the U.S., as well as some interesting opportunities in other areas of the world.




                  What’s next for your business and why are you raising money now?
                  



Up until now, we've been bootstrapping, with a goal of getting the fundamentals right. We have succeeded in developing a direct-to-consumer model in an industry that traditionally does not take that approach. We have worked on bringing down our acquisition costs, our R&D costs, and fine-tuned the e-commerce side of things. Although there is always more to learn, we're on the right track.

The next step is ramping up growth, first by bringing new products to the market. To that end, we are involved in the internal development of a new product that will be for sale early in 2017.

We also plan to introduce new and recurring revenue streams, starting with the bike-as-a-service approach that I mentioned earlier. Options like theft protection or annual maintenance plans are a real opportunity to turn a $2,800 one-time bike purchase into a monthly subscription to additional service offerings. At the same time, we intend to venture outside of the U.S. market, beginning with expansion into Canada next year. With a similar market and geography, expansion into Canada carries limited risk and lets us fine-tune our distribution techniques. By applying these same techniques to the much larger European market, we will find a profitable niche there that features competitive pricing at 500-1,000 Euros less than European pricing.




                  What’s been your largest challenge so far?
                  



Ironically enough, our biggest challenge came from our major strength -- offering a direct-to-consumer model. Most of the packaging used in the bike industry isn’t designed to effectively protect the product when individual boxes are shipped to customers via cost-effective shippers like FedEx or UPS. At first, we experienced significant damage on up to 25% of shipped bikes resulting from transit through various hubs or centers on its way to its destination, as well as sometimes less-than-stellar treatment during the final trip to the customer’s door. Obviously, this is a poor customer experience and is very costly to deal with, even in cases where our damage claims were accepted by the shipper. We needed another solution. So we experimented with designing packaging that would survive and protect the bike no matter what UPS or FedEx could throw at it. With that challenge solved, shipping damage affects less than half a percent of orders (fewer than 1 in 200 bikes).




                  This is an unusual fundraising strategy. Why have you given your customers the chance to invest online via Wefunder?
                  



We did a small friends and family/seed round last year and also emailed our customer base about our vision for the company. We were blown away by the degree of interest – in fact, two customers wound up investing around $250,000.

But last year we had to turn away many potential investors because they were not accredited investors. With the growth in our customer base and contacts this year, we hope to gain real traction now that the barrier of accreditation has been removed. Having more of our customers have the opportunity to invest in EVELO and expand our relationship with them is an important part of our vision of the company vis-à-vis our customers.




                  Can you tell us about the team? Why are you the ones to make this happen?
                  



My brother and I have been involved in start-ups for the last 10 years or so. Prior to launching EVELO, I was employee number 3 in one of the first person-to-person car sharing dotcoms, which was sort of a hybrid of AirBNB and ZipCar. My main focus there was marketing and customer acquisition. That company went on to raise over $90 million from DC, including Google Ventures, and then expanded nationwide. It was an invaluable learning experience on how to scale a company within a new industry.

About half of our team has extensive experience with traditional bike companies, including a former executive from a large bike brand and another who has worked with one of the largest electrical bike retail operations in North America. Our sales and service teams are comprised of individuals who have previous experience selling and servicing bikes, and all have the knowledge and interest in the industry that is vital to our ongoing success.

But one thing that makes our team really special is that it's the perfect hybrid of those with experience in the traditional bicycle industry and those with e-commerce skills and experience. Our marketing and logistics teams have much experience in online ecommerce in general, covering everything from search engine optimization and online advertising, through online marketing and social media, as well as the logistics needed to make this kind of business a success. This combination of skills in those involved at EVELO creates a powerful synergy that has – and will continue -- to fuel our growth in the coming years.














